Trading Update - FY26 R&E & CTI Targets Abandoned

BOQ expects FY25 cash earnings of between A\$375m and A\$385m, in line with both prior JEFE and VAE. It also guided to a 50- 70bp yoy increase in ROE, which was below JEFE and VAE. BOQ is no longer providing specific FY26 ROE and CTI targets to the market, which we think is unsurprising given how ambitious they were. We shift FY25/26/27 EPS by 1%/- 1%/- 1% on M2M volume adjustments and lower BDDS, and reiterate our UNPF recommendation.
BOQ has introduced FY25 cash earnings and ROE guidance, while walking away from its previous FY26 financial targets. It also provided two strategic updates. Specifically:

FY25 performance: i) FY25 cash earnings of between A\$375m- A\$385m. Guidance was in line with prior JEFE/VAE (\\$378m), but there are \$66m of incremental below- the- line adjustments, which is A\$56m more than prior JEFE, which is equivalent to 14bp of CET1. ii) Management has also guided to a 50- 70bp yoy increase in ROE (FY24 5.5%) vs. prior JEFE +93bp. We find it difficult to reconcile the guided ROE given that cash earnings guidance assumes 11% growth at the mid- point, while average equity had decreased 7% hoh in 2H24 and 3% hoh in 1H25.

FY26 financial targets: BOQ is no longer providing specific FY26 ROE and cost- to- income ratio targets (previous 8% and 56% respectively), which we think is unsurprising and is consistent with our previously disclosed views (here). Management suggested that economic and societal headwinds have led to this decision.

Strategy Update: i) Exploring a whole- of- loan sale process for up to \(\sim \mathrm{A}\$ 3.8bn\) of its equipment finance portfolio, including a forward flow origination and servicing arrangement. Management expects this to improve ROE and to be EPS- accretive over time. However, assuming a buyback of the capital released (JEFE c.\\$350m), we see this bar as low, given i) management noted the ROE of the equipment finance business is below the broader group ROE, and ii) the stock, tades at a discount to book value. To this end, our high- level analysis suggests the deal would be 1% EPS accretive if BOQ only earned 21bp of servicing revenue, consistent with the 20- 30bp PPM AU (not covered) earns on equivalent transactions. Furthermore, this is bigger any gain on sale, which, over time, has averaged c.1% of loans sold for PPM. ii) Entered into a strategic partnership with Capgemini for agentic AI business processing services, anticipates realising annualised cost savings of at least A\$30mn from FY27.
We shift EPS by 1%/- 1%/- 1% for FY25/26/27 and reiterate Underperform

EPS changes have been driven by: i) a M2M on volumes, ii) a stronger NIM mix, and iii) lower BDDS. As a result of our EPS changes, a roll- forward of our 12- mo forward valuation date and a M2M of comparative company multiples, our PT moves up 3% to \$5.84, implying a - 21% total shareholder return, and so we remain Underperform.
Please see analyst certifications, important disclosure information, and information regarding the status of non-US analysts on pages 5 - 11 of this report. \\* Jefferies (Australia) Pty Ltd

Investment Thesis / Where We Differ

BOQ is dramatically evolving its business model by corporatising its Owner- Managed Branches (OMBs), which was historically seen as a growth differentiator. Furthermore, transaction deposits (at \(8\%\) and falling) are less than half those at BEN and less than a third of the major bank average, and the bank is also faced with regulatory burdens to improve its risk culture. In response to this, its productivity program is aggressive, with A\$250m of costs targeted by FY26 (25% of its FY23A cost base). However, given execution and broader franchise risks, we struggle to see BOQ materially improving its targeted metrics from current levels (FY26E JEFe CTI/ROE of \(63\% /6\%\) vs. \(56\% /8\%\) target).
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

Upside Scenario, AUD10.78, +37%

Downside Scenario, AUD4.52, - 43%
For our downside scenario, we factor in a 4.5x trough P/PPOP multiple and apply a \(5\%\) downside. The other DCF inputs are left unchanged.

Bank of Queensland LimitedBank of Queensland Limited (BOQ) is Australia's 6th largest retail bank. Established in 1874, the Bank operates in two segments which are Retail Banking and Business Banking. Retail Banking provides solutions to customers through their Owner- Managed and Corporate branch network, third party intermediaries and Virgin Money Australia distribution channels. BOQ Business includes the BOQ branded commercial lending activity, BOQ Specialist and BOQ Finance businesses. The division provides business banking solutions tailored to clients' needs, including commercial lending, equipment finance and leasing, cashflow finance, foreign exchange, interest rate hedging, transaction banking and deposit solutions for commercial customers. BOQ shares and related securities are listed on the ASX.

Valuation: Base case valuation is premised on 13bp mid-cycle loan loss charge, an \(10\%\) cum-div CET1 and a 50/50 blend of a DCF, incorporating a \(4\%\) risk-free rate, \(5.5\%\) market risk premium and 1.5 beta, and P/NTA with a market imputed cost of capital of \(6.8\%\)

Risks: 1) Successful execution of both the corporatisation of 114 OMB's and pivot towards higher margin specialist business banking division. 2) Navigation of the final stages of ME Bank integration. 3) A continuation of the benign asset quality environment, particularly in QLD. 4) A reversal in BOQ's ability for the bank to attract low-cost deposits as a source of funding.

Valuation: Base case valuation is premised on 11bp mid-cycle loan loss charge, an \(10\%\) cum-div CET1 and a 50/50 blend of a DCF, incorporating a \(4\%\) risk-free rate, \(5.5\%\) market risk premium and 1.5 beta, and P/NTA with a market imputed cost of capital of \(8.2\%\)

Risks: 1) Continued increase in margin pressure, with the impact of higher deposit costs from both more customers chasing better returns in term deposits and rising spreads in wholesale funding markets making it more expensive to compete on mortgages in a falling cash rate environment. 2) Heightened regional Australia exposure, vulnerable to economic downturns in housing and agriculture within these regions. 3) Successfully navigating the final stages of their vast transformation project (1 core banking system & 3 brands by Jun-25).

We value Capgemini using IT Services peer group multiples on a December FY26E FCF yield. Risks to our price target include lower- than- expected IT services spending, higher- than- expected wage inflation, and Altran acquisition integration risks.

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period. Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period.
